<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="229" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,463,1763]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1663,1688]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[326,613,1663,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cothornobata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegantula">
<emphasis box="[326,613,1663,1688]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">Cothornobata elegantula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[779,863,1664,1687]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cothornobata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atra" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[779,863,1664,1687]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">C. atra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[874,968,1663,1688]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[874,968,1663,1688]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but differs as follows: postocellar seta present; bm-cu proximal to CuA 
<number box="[515,523,1714,1728]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" value="2.0">2</number>
; postgonite slender and strongly bent, creating a “V-shape”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1388,1738,1763]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,463,1763]" box="[199,1388,1738,1763]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1738,1763]" pageId="28" pageNumber="229">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name refers to the postgonite which forms an “elegant” and distinctive structure.
</paragraph>
